07561nam a22008295i 9783110534696DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2018948744  a97831105346967 a10.1515/97831105346962doi  a(DE-B1597)477513  a(OCoLC)1059281002  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aHC240b.P572 2018 7aHIS0540002bisacsh04a330.9405500aPlanning in Cold War Europe :bCompetition, Cooperation, Circulations (1950s-1970s) /ced. by Michel Christian, Sandrine Kott, Ondrej Matejka. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (VIII, 375 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRethinking the Cold War ,x2567-5311 ;v200tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tTable of Contents -- tPlanning in Cold War Europe: Introduction -- tPart 1: Planning a New World after the War -- tPeace, Prosperity and Planning Postwar Trade, 1942-1948 -- tA Bridge between East and West? Gunnar Myrdal and the UN Economic Commission for Europe, 1947-1957 -- tPart 2: High Modernism Planning -- tMandatory Planning versus Indicative Planning? The Eastern Itinerary of French Planners (1960s-1970s) -- tInternational Research Planning across the Iron Curtain: East-Central European Social Scientists in the ISSC and Vienna Centre -- tThe Social Engineering Project. Exportation of Capitalist Management Culture to Eastern Europe (1950-1980) -- tTransferring Western Knowledge to a centrally planned Economy: Finland and the Scientific-Technical Cooperation with the Soviet Union -- tSocial Engineering and Alienation between East and West: Czech Christian-Marxist Dialogue in the 1960s from the National Level to the Global Arena -- tThe Council for Mutual Economic Assistance and the failed Coordination of Planning in the Socialist Bloc in the 1960s -- tPart 3: Alternatives to Planning -- tLearning from Yugoslavia? Western Europe and the Myth of Self-Management (1968-1975) -- tManaging Socialist Industrialism: Czechoslovak Management Studies in the 1960s and 1970s -- tEcosystems Research and Policy Planning: Revisiting the Budworm Project (1972-1980) at the IIASA -- t"It is not a Question of rigidly Planning Trade" UNCTAD and the Regulation of the International Trade in the 1970s -- tPlanning the Future of World Markets: the OECD's Interfuturs Project -- tWorks Cited0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe book opens new perspectives on the global Cold War by looking at social and economic planning. Despite the rival visions of the world that they put forward, social regulating ideas and practices were also at the core of a common project of modernity. This volume will show how social and economic knowledge circulated globally and how it was reinterpreted and appropriated in various national and local contexts.  aThe idea of planning economy and engineering social life has often been linked with Communist regimes' will of control. However, the persuasion that social and economic processes could and should be regulated was by no means limited to them. Intense debates on these issues developed already during the First World War in Europe and became globalized during the World Economic crisis. During the Cold War, such discussions fuelled competition between two models of economic and social organisation but they also revealed the convergences and complementarities between them. This ambiguity, so often overlooked in histories of the Cold War, represents the central issue of the book organized around three axes. First, it highlights how know-how on planning circulated globally and were exchanged by looking at international platforms and organizations. The volume then closely examines specificities of planning ideas and projects in the Communist and Capitalist World. Finally, it explores East-West channels generated by exchanges around issues of planning which functioned irrespective of the Iron Curtain and were exported in developing countries. The volume thus contributes to two fields undergoing a process of profound reassessment: the history of modernisation and of the Cold War.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCold War. 4aInternationale Organisation. 4aKalter Krieg. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh1 aAndersson, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAutio-Sarasmo, Sari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristian, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristian, Michel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGodard, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGouarné, Isabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutter, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKott, Sandrine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKott, Sandrine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMatejka, Ondrej, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMatějka, Ondřej, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKenzie, Francine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichel, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaumann, Katja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSommer, Vítězslav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStinsky, Daniel, 